===Glyph origin===
{{Han etym}}
In the oracle script, this character was an {{Han compound|人|子|ls=ic|t1=person|t2=child|nocap=1}} – a person carrying a child on his back; to carry (a child) > to protect. See also [[好]].

In early bronze inscriptions, {{zh-l|*爪|hand}} was added to the person to emphasize that the person was carrying the child. This was later simplified into one or two strokes. The current form has two.

===Etymology===
From {{inh|zh|sit-pro|*puʔ|t=to carry (on back or shoulders)}}. Cognate with {{och-l|抱|to heft, hug}}; see there for more (STEDT).

